2
00:00:07,592 --> 00:00:08,633
My name is David Helsby.

3
00:00:08,653 --> 00:00:11,195
I'm a senior animator at Bungie Studios,

4
00:00:11,516 --> 00:00:13,638
and I've been there for about six years.

5
00:00:14,158 --> 00:00:17,902
My game credits at Bungie are Halo Reach and now Destiny

6
00:00:17,962 --> 00:00:19,364
and subsequent DLCs.

7
00:00:19,444 --> 00:00:21,306
And yeah.

8
00:00:22,347 --> 00:00:24,769
So I want to start out by asking you a question.

9
00:00:25,690 --> 00:00:28,793
And that is, what makes a Bungie game feel like a Bungie game?

10
00:00:29,822 --> 00:00:32,464
Well, a lot goes into creating the first person experience,

11
00:00:32,544 --> 00:00:34,525
but first person is something that's

12
00:00:34,545 --> 00:00:37,086
going to affect how the game plays and feels

13
00:00:37,146 --> 00:00:38,447
on a moment-to-moment basis.

14
00:00:39,127 --> 00:00:43,089
And many of you may not even notice it if it's done right.

15
00:00:45,390 --> 00:00:47,711
So this talk is going to be split up into three parts.

16
00:00:48,311 --> 00:00:50,593
So first we're going to talk about supporting

17
00:00:50,613 --> 00:00:51,993
the goals of sandbox design.

18
00:00:53,552 --> 00:00:57,274
Secondly, we're going to talk about making first-person content that feels good.

19
00:00:57,914 --> 00:00:59,655
And what does feels good mean, really?

20
00:01:00,315 --> 00:01:01,336
I'm going to talk about that later.

21
00:01:02,056 --> 00:01:06,619
And finally, I'm going to talk to you about how to keep from killing yourself in the process of making a game.

22
00:01:07,519 --> 00:01:11,821
And for all of you game developers out there, I'm sure you know what I'm talking about.

23
00:01:14,703 --> 00:01:16,084
So, what is first-person animation?

24
00:01:16,873 --> 00:01:22,614
Well, first-person animation is just the animation, it's the movement of your avatar from your

25
00:01:22,854 --> 00:01:25,254
perspective as a player, including the player camera.

26
00:01:25,894 --> 00:01:31,595
So all that motion you see, I mean, some designers have really told me that this is the most

27
00:01:31,635 --> 00:01:36,676
important animation in a first-person shooter, and whether you believe that or not, doing

28
00:01:36,696 --> 00:01:40,597
this content well is something that's definitely going to help the playability of the game,

29
00:01:40,777 --> 00:01:43,297
and more importantly, the replayability of your game.

30
00:01:45,278 --> 00:01:45,398
So.

31
00:01:46,749 --> 00:01:49,650
Let's get started. Supporting the goals of sandbox design.

32
00:01:51,751 --> 00:01:54,912
Now, design and art don't always see eye to eye.

33
00:01:56,292 --> 00:01:58,773
Art wants to make an amazing player attack

34
00:01:59,354 --> 00:02:02,235
that has like three seconds of anticipation,

35
00:02:02,275 --> 00:02:05,676
while design wants an attack that hits one frame after the player hits the button.

36
00:02:06,712 --> 00:02:08,313
Well, to build a new IP of Bungie,

37
00:02:08,333 --> 00:02:10,313
I really needed to know how to best support

38
00:02:10,493 --> 00:02:13,614
the goals of sandbox design and build enough trust

39
00:02:13,654 --> 00:02:16,314
to try and push the artistic side of Destiny's first person

40
00:02:16,354 --> 00:02:17,175
experience forward.

41
00:02:18,055 --> 00:02:19,975
So we came up with a set of design directives

42
00:02:20,035 --> 00:02:22,056
for first person we called Design Pillars.

43
00:02:24,296 --> 00:02:28,677
So this is my first talk that I'm giving at GDC.

44
00:02:28,697 --> 00:02:30,258
And when you're putting a talk like this together,

45
00:02:30,298 --> 00:02:31,738
you want to sound really prepared

46
00:02:31,758 --> 00:02:33,598
and you want to sound like you know what you're doing, right?

47
00:02:34,438 --> 00:02:38,041
And so when I, in my first incarnation of this talk,

48
00:02:38,081 --> 00:02:39,222
I was gonna say, yeah, you know,

49
00:02:39,242 --> 00:02:40,603
we made these design pillars,

50
00:02:40,703 --> 00:02:43,606
and we made them at the beginning of the project,

51
00:02:43,646 --> 00:02:45,007
and then we just followed that,

52
00:02:45,067 --> 00:02:47,069
and everything went super cool, right?

53
00:02:47,950 --> 00:02:49,571
And I gave this, I gave this kind of a,

54
00:02:49,731 --> 00:02:52,694
this first talk to one of our sandbox director,

55
00:02:52,714 --> 00:02:54,755
and he's like, he's like, what are you doing?

56
00:02:55,596 --> 00:02:56,497
He's like, tell the truth.

57
00:02:58,255 --> 00:02:59,316
And I was like, alright.

58
00:02:59,956 --> 00:03:01,958
So the truth is, we came up with these

59
00:03:03,239 --> 00:03:06,761
these pillars of first-person design, like, after the project was finished.

60
00:03:07,242 --> 00:03:10,524
I sat down with it, and I'm like, what do we really do here? What's important?

61
00:03:11,225 --> 00:03:15,068
He's like, oh, okay, yeah, you know, we did this and this, and I'm like, alright, cool.

62
00:03:15,828 --> 00:03:17,350
Now, for the next game, we'll know.

63
00:03:18,330 --> 00:03:19,952
So, here are our pillars.

64
00:03:20,392 --> 00:03:22,574
And you guys get them for free, you don't have to go through the pain we went through.

65
00:03:24,391 --> 00:03:28,873
The first one is just immediate feedback from the player controller input.

66
00:03:28,973 --> 00:03:31,734
And that just means like you hit a button and you get an action.

67
00:03:32,495 --> 00:03:35,756
And if you think about it, your brain's already told you what you want to do.

68
00:03:35,856 --> 00:03:39,058
So if you hit the button, you don't get an immediate response.

69
00:03:39,298 --> 00:03:43,160
It feels wrong. It feels like there's a disconnect between you and the game.

70
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:47,462
So the minute that button gets pushed,

71
00:03:47,482 --> 00:03:49,723
you want to start seeing motion on the screen, like immediately.

72
00:03:51,229 --> 00:03:53,811
Secondly is the preservation of motion between actions.

73
00:03:53,911 --> 00:03:56,914
It just means everything has to flow smoothly

74
00:03:56,974 --> 00:03:58,195
from one motion to the other.

75
00:03:58,335 --> 00:04:01,478
And we've gotten past the point where we can do a motion,

76
00:04:01,538 --> 00:04:03,459
it comes back to an idle and hits a wall,

77
00:04:03,499 --> 00:04:04,781
and then you do another motion.

78
00:04:04,821 --> 00:04:06,422
You need to be able to design animations

79
00:04:06,442 --> 00:04:07,803
that chain together effectively.

80
00:04:10,547 --> 00:04:15,050
So the third one is the player should have visceral satisfaction from your animation.

81
00:04:15,570 --> 00:04:19,492
Now this doesn't mean like, oh, make something cool, make a cool reload.

82
00:04:19,532 --> 00:04:24,055
This means think about the player, think about each thing as a player experience.

83
00:04:24,815 --> 00:04:27,957
And that means like, if I'm going to make like a really cool melee or reload,

84
00:04:27,977 --> 00:04:32,120
I need design and sound and effects all on board,

85
00:04:32,220 --> 00:04:35,121
because if we're all not working toward the same goal,

86
00:04:35,582 --> 00:04:38,563
toward the same player experience, it's not going to be as good as it could be.

87
00:04:41,564 --> 00:04:45,268
Four is, motion should serve to ground the player to the world.

88
00:04:45,948 --> 00:04:48,732
Now, first person is really an interactive experience,

89
00:04:48,832 --> 00:04:50,954
or an immersive experience.

90
00:04:50,974 --> 00:04:54,999
So you should really feel like, you should feel physical.

91
00:04:55,019 --> 00:04:56,781
You should feel like there's a body behind the camera.

92
00:04:58,874 --> 00:05:02,756
And finally, this is one that I thought was really interesting and it didn't come on until very late.

93
00:05:02,896 --> 00:05:06,237
At least, my true understanding of it, which is no speed bumps.

94
00:05:06,777 --> 00:05:11,679
And that just means we don't want to take control away from the player or slow him down in the sandbox as much as possible.

95
00:05:12,540 --> 00:05:17,682
And like, analogy of that is like, you're, you've got a really fast car. You've been given like a Ferrari.

96
00:05:17,722 --> 00:05:19,463
The last thing you want to do is go for a speed bump.

97
00:05:19,643 --> 00:05:23,985
You want to be on a straightaway. That car is meant to be driven fast, so drive it fast.

98
00:05:25,557 --> 00:05:29,418
So, this is the last time I'm gonna assault you guys with a wall of text. I promise.

99
00:05:30,158 --> 00:05:34,620
So, but I will be mentioning some of these things, you know, as the talk goes on.

100
00:05:34,640 --> 00:05:36,921
But I boiled them down to like two main principles.

101
00:05:38,041 --> 00:05:40,842
And one is support fast, fun, responsive gameplay.

102
00:05:43,143 --> 00:05:48,285
And two, make it feel like a body, your body is behind the camera. Make it feel physical.

103
00:05:49,225 --> 00:05:52,866
Now this is, this is the hard part, because trying to do both of these, both of these

104
00:05:52,906 --> 00:05:54,587
things at the same time can sometimes...

105
00:05:55,594 --> 00:05:58,176
seem impossible, but there's where the challenge and the fun comes in.

106
00:05:59,336 --> 00:05:59,596
Sort of.

107
00:06:02,258 --> 00:06:02,478
So,

108
00:06:03,719 --> 00:06:06,860
let's move on to, now that we've talked about design principles and

109
00:06:07,361 --> 00:06:09,622
what we want to do and how we want to do it, let's talk about

110
00:06:10,302 --> 00:06:12,123
how to make first-person content that feels good.

111
00:06:14,660 --> 00:06:15,901
What does feels good mean?

112
00:06:16,381 --> 00:06:18,362
Well first, I mean we've gotten some information already.

113
00:06:18,963 --> 00:06:22,405
We want to support first person that supports this fast, fun,

114
00:06:22,566 --> 00:06:23,666
and responsive gameplay.

115
00:06:24,287 --> 00:06:25,468
And we want to make it feel like there's

116
00:06:25,488 --> 00:06:27,709
a body behind the camera, something that feels physical.

117
00:06:28,330 --> 00:06:30,531
But like the last thing, the last piece of information

118
00:06:30,632 --> 00:06:34,294
is, don't get in the way of the player's gameplay experience.

119
00:06:34,334 --> 00:06:35,335
Don't get in the way of their fun.

120
00:06:35,635 --> 00:06:39,718
Your content is not more important than the player's fun.

121
00:06:39,998 --> 00:06:41,680
And that's one of the main things

122
00:06:41,700 --> 00:06:44,102
to remember about making first person animation.

123
00:06:46,779 --> 00:06:50,780
So, this is what Destiny looks like without any first-person animation.

124
00:06:51,380 --> 00:06:55,141
And this is the same player presets, everything exactly the same,

125
00:06:55,181 --> 00:06:57,841
except you're not getting the visual feedback from first-person.

126
00:06:59,542 --> 00:07:03,802
And it feels like you're just kind of a floating camera inhabiting the world.

127
00:07:03,842 --> 00:07:07,483
It doesn't feel like there's any person behind the screen.

128
00:07:08,263 --> 00:07:10,384
So, we want to change that.

129
00:07:10,404 --> 00:07:12,344
We want to start drawing you into our world.

